Subject: CardConnect - Shift4 Deal 08-21-18

Jeff,
I wanted to follow up on our call earlier today. Our position is pretty simple.

•	 We put together a great deal for Card Connect that resulted in several hundred million in present day value and the acquisition of a competitor that was (at the time) many multiple times larger than Card Connect.
•	 We have always fulfilled our end of the bargain on every commitment we have made.
•	 It seems Card Connect, for whatever reason, has not managed their business effectively as evidenced by constant profit warnings, falling short of financial commitments, etc.
•		Card Connect agreed to deliver $7.5M in annual revenue on the Shift4 base as part of the transaction which, at an absolute minimum, would compensate us for the risk of taking so much stock at the time (~$90M). This was an important part of us getting comfortable with a majority stock transaction.
•	 You have also indicated Card Connect would not make the additional $3.5M payment this year that was also agreed upon as part of the original transaction.
•	 We met a few weeks ago at your office where you requested a number of changes to scoring, unfunded, at-risk parameters throughout the merchant application process. This all occurred without any input from us – yet we were not compensated for any of those Card Connect decisions.
•	 We agreed to extend the shortfall period an additional year to compensate for those changes and Card Connect putting the brakes on boarding merchants in early 2018 so an operational improvement plan could be put in place.
•		We believe strongly that the full $7.5M per year in revenue will easily be achieved by 2020, if not sooner.

        Considering the above, we are fine ending our present agreement at the conclusion of 2019 with some modest economics to compensate for changes you requested in at-risk, unfunded and other merchant application scoring changes. It’s a no brainer for Card Connect. We would be open to discuss a new, different program from 2020 onward if it made sense for both parties.

Thanks,
Jared

Jared Isaacman
